      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "93c01c4f-2389-4f03-b6f8-6cd4567b9994",
        "score": 0.7172022,
        "text": "The document outlines the participation requirements for Market Participants in the CAISO Markets. Key points include:\n\n1. **Direct Participation Requirements**: \n   - Participants must have a net worth of $1 million, total assets of $5 million, or credit support from a guaranty or Letter of Credit from a qualified entity.\n   - Participants who no longer meet these requirements must notify CAISO and cease participation.\n\n2. **Minimum Participation Requirements**:\n   - Participants must provide certified statements (Officer Certification Forms), adhere to risk management policies, and meet capitalization requirements.\n\n3. **Certified Statements (Officer Certification Forms)**:\n   - Participants with a direct financial relationship with CAISO must submit an annual Officer Certification Form.\n   - The initial form is required during the registration process, and updates are due by April 30 each year.\n   - Failure to submit the form results in suspension from the CAISO Markets until compliance is met.\n\n4. **Certification Criteria**:\n   - Participants must certify that they have undergone appropriate training related to transaction volume and risk, as specified in the CAISO Tariff.\n\nThe document emphasizes compliance with financial and procedural standards to maintain market participation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Credit_Management_&_Market_Clearing/page_21.jpg",
          "page_num": 21,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Credit Management & Market Clearing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a353a32f-4346-443d-bc1c-b5f0341b6d26",
        "score": 0.7088975,
        "text": "The document outlines the certification requirements for SC (Scheduling Coordinator) Applicants to participate in the CAISO (California Independent System Operator) Markets. Once an application is accepted, a CAISO representative will initiate the certification process. Applicants intending to use a Scheduling Agent must submit a letter of agency with their application.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Financial Security and Participation Requirements**: \n   - Applicants must meet the financial security requirements as per FERC Order 741 and the CAISO Tariff.\n   - Financial security can be established through unsecured credit or approved financial forms.\n   - Information submitted for financial security is confidential.\n\n2. **Minimum Participation Requirements**:\n   - Applicants should understand these requirements before submitting their application.\n   - The process takes about ten business days.\n   - Requirements can be satisfied by having a net worth of $1 million, total assets of $10 million, or credit support from a qualified entity.\n\nAttachment A provides a summary of these certification requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Scheduling_Coordinator_Certification_&_Termination_and_Convergence_Bidding_Entity_Registration_&_Termination/page_21.jpg",
          "page_num": 21,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Scheduling Coordinator Certification & Termination and Convergence Bidding Entity Registration & Termination",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8927a914-116a-4343-a3a8-851bd2c8e61d",
        "score": 0.6673983,
        "text": "The document outlines the capitalization requirements for prospective or existing Market Participants in the CAISO (California Independent System Operator) markets. Key points include:\n\n1. **Capitalization Requirements**: \n   - Participants or their guarantors must have at least $1 million in Tangible Net Worth or $10 million in total assets.\n   - Alternatively, they can post Financial Security as specified in Section 5.1 of the BPM.\n\n2. **Financial Security**:\n   - Financial Security cannot be used to meet minimum credit requirements for certain market activities, such as Congestion Revenue Rights auctions.\n   - It can be used to satisfy any financial obligations of the Market Participant.\n\n3. **Market Activity and Liability**:\n   - Participants with less than six months of market activity must have $500,000 in Financial Security.\n   - Those with six months or more of activity and an Estimated Aggregate Liability of $100,000 or less must have $100,000 in Financial Security.\n   - If the liability exceeds $100,000, the Financial Security must match the highest liability.\n\n4. **Review and Compliance**:\n   - CAISO reviews compliance every six months or when financial statements are updated.\n   - Participants are notified of changes in requirements and have 20 business days to comply.\n\n5. **Certification and Eligibility**:\n   - Participants must meet all requirements in Section 12.1 of the CAISO Tariff to participate in the markets.\n   - Non-compliance results in ineligibility to become a Market Participant or CRR Holder.\n\nThis ensures that all participants maintain adequate financial stability to engage in CAISO markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Credit_Management_&_Market_Clearing/page_23.jpg",
          "page_num": 23,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Credit Management & Market Clearing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1c8ee8f3-b671-4441-b754-10e3b0ea44b7",
        "score": 0.6634536,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for Market Participants involved in CRR (Congestion Revenue Rights) trading within the CAISO (California Independent System Operator) markets. It emphasizes the need for these participants to maintain comprehensive risk management frameworks that address credit, liquidity, and market risks. Participants must have written policies and procedures approved by their governing bodies and demonstrate adherence to industry risk management standards.\n\nAdditionally, Market Participants must have adequate personnel and procedures to respond to CAISO communications, including handling invoices and collateral requests. The document also specifies that CRR Holders or Candidates must submit risk management policies and controls to CAISO, ensuring they align with accepted practices. Any modifications to these policies require prompt submission to CAISO for review. Participation in CRR markets is contingent upon CAISO's acceptance of these risk management practices.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Credit_Management_&_Market_Clearing/page_22.jpg",
          "page_num": 22,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Credit Management & Market Clearing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5d868e14-a7e1-48e4-bcab-257aa8a105ac",
        "score": 0.6598258,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for entities submitting bids to the California Independent System Operator (CAISO). Each entity must execute an agreement with CAISO and designate a certified Scheduling Coordinator (SC) to represent them. The entities include:\n\n1. **Participating Transmission Owners (PTOs):** Must use a certified SC to submit bids. Bids are only accepted from the entity's Responsible PTO.\n\n2. **Non-Participating Transmission Owners (Non-PTOs):** Must use a certified SC and submit bids using Transmission Ownership Right (TOR) Self-Schedules. Non-PTOs must submit specific transmission instructions to CAISO.\n\n3. **Generating Units:** Generators, including those with Qualifying Facilities, must use a certified SC to submit bids. Bids are only accepted from certified SCs.\n\n4. **Load Serving Entities (LSEs):** Must use a certified SC to submit bids for energy supply and ancillary services. An executed Meter Service Agreement for SCs (MSA SC) is required.\n\n5. **Demand Response Providers (DRPs):** Must use a certified SC to submit bids and act as a proxy for Demand Resources. An executed MSA SC is required for Proxy Demand Resources.\n\nThe document emphasizes the necessity of certified SCs and proper agreements for all entities involved in bidding processes with CAISO.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Scheduling_Coordinator_Certification_&_Termination_and_Convergence_Bidding_Entity_Registration_&_Termination/page_9.jpg",
          "page_num": 9,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Scheduling Coordinator Certification & Termination and Convergence Bidding Entity Registration & Termination",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "54a01d5c-5d8c-46c2-b4cc-9623c3b6d267",
        "score": 0.6585589,
        "text": "The document outlines the creditworthiness and minimum participation requirements for transactions in the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) Market. Key points include:\n\n1. **Creditworthiness Requirements**: \n   - Participants must secure financial transactions with CAISO by maintaining an Unsecured Credit Limit or posting Financial Security.\n   - The sum of a participant's Unsecured Credit Limit and Financial Security Amount should represent its Aggregate Credit Limit, which must be at least equal to its Estimated Aggregate Liability.\n\n2. **Participation Requirements**:\n   - Prospective or existing market participants must provide an annual certified statement to CAISO, confirming compliance with criteria in the Business Practice Manual.\n   - Participants must undergo training proportional to their transaction volume and risk exposure, meeting CAISO's specified training requirements.\n\nThese requirements ensure financial security and proper training for market participants engaging in CAISO auctions and transactions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_447.jpg",
          "page_num": 447,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "76d44512-7ed6-4f4a-8ed3-d3764b62dbef",
        "score": 0.6537039,
        "text": "The document outlines requirements for submitting bids to the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) for various entities:\n\n1. **Eligible Intermittent Resources**: Must become or obtain services of a certified Scheduling Coordinator (SC) to submit bids. CAISO does not accept bids without a certified SC.\n\n2. **System Resources**: Must also become or obtain services of a certified SC. Additional requirements include:\n   - **Resource-Specific System Resources**: Must register with CAISO, have a Resource ID, and provide operational characteristics similar to a CAISO Balancing Authority Area unit.\n   - **Non-Resource-Specific System Resources**: Must register the Scheduling Point and unique ID for scheduling purposes.\n\n   Types of System Resources:\n   - **Non-Dynamic**: Do not meet CAISO's requirements for a Dynamic Schedule.\n   - **Dynamic**: Meet CAISO's requirements for a Dynamic Schedule.\n   - **Non-Dynamic Resource-Specific**: Non-Dynamic resources outside the CAISO Balancing Authority Area.\n   - **Dynamic Resource-Specific**: Dynamic resources outside the CAISO Balancing Authority Area.\n\n3. **Utility Distribution Companies (UDCs)**: Must become or obtain services of a certified SC to submit bids. CAISO does not accept bids without a certified SC.\n\n4. **Metered Subsystems (MSSs)**: Must become or obtain services of a certified SC to submit bids. CAISO does not accept bids without a certified SC.\n\n5. **Convergence Bidding Entities**: Must become or obtain services of a certified SC to participate in the convergence bidding market.\n\nThe document is effective from March 1, 2025, and is part of the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Scheduling Coordinator Certification & Termination and Convergence Bidding Entity Registration & Termination.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Scheduling_Coordinator_Certification_&_Termination_and_Convergence_Bidding_Entity_Registration_&_Termination/page_10.jpg",
          "page_num": 10,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Scheduling Coordinator Certification & Termination and Convergence Bidding Entity Registration & Termination",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "149cb1d7-d31e-42b3-b172-eaa1bbfa431c",
        "score": 0.6431907,
        "text": "The document is a section from the CAISO Business Practice Manual focused on the Credit Policy Overview. It outlines:\n\n1. **Credit Policy Overview**: \n   - Details who is subject to the credit policy and its goals.\n   - Explains the principles of credit policy operation.\n   - Provides contact information for questions regarding the credit policy.\n   - Offers an overview of the sections in the BPM.\n\n2. **Credit Policy Applicability and Goal**:\n   - All Market Participants requesting transmission services with CAISO must meet specific participation requirements.\n   - Participants must adhere to the credit policy as per Section 12 of the CAISO Tariff.\n   - The policy aims to protect Market Participants from undue financial risk.\n\n3. **Minimum Criteria for Direct Participation**:\n   - Participants must qualify as an \"appropriate person\" or \"eligible contract participant\" as per the Commodity Exchange Act.\n   - They must be involved in generating, transmitting, or distributing electric energy.\n   - Alternatively, they can participate as a Scheduling Coordinator, provided they are not involved in certain other roles and are engaged in providing necessary electric energy services.\n\nThese requirements are in addition to the Minimum Participation Requirements, and most entities can meet them by fulfilling one or more specified conditions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Credit_Management_&_Market_Clearing/page_20.jpg",
          "page_num": 20,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Credit Management & Market Clearing",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "30322a8b-3ad6-4af3-badf-5d71d2b31d93",
        "score": 0.6381501,
        "text": "The document is a page from the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Scheduling Coordinator Certification and Termination. It includes a \"Scheduling Coordinator Application Form\" for certification by the California Independent System Operator Corporation (CAISO) under the CAISO Tariff. The application is confidential and consists of two main sections:\n\n1. **Section I: Administrative Requirements**\n   - **Applicant's Legal Name**: Must be consistent across all documentation to avoid delays.\n   - **Scheduling Coordinator ID (SCID)**: Applicants must provide three options for their SCID, which is a unique identifier in CAISO Market systems.\n   - **Address Details**: Includes street address, city, state, and zip code.\n   - **State of Incorporation or Partnership**: If applicable.\n   - **Proposed Commencement Date for Service**: When the service is expected to start.\n   - **Entity Type**: Options include municipal utility, power marketer, investor-owned utility, etc.\n   - **Use of Scheduling Agent Services**: Applicants must indicate if they plan to use these services.\n\n2. **Section II: Scheduling Coordinator Customer Information**\n   - Applicants must certify their authorization to represent Generators and Loads as Scheduling Coordinator Customers.\n   - They must confirm that:\n     - Generators have entered into necessary agreements with CAISO.\n     - UDCs have entered into UDC Operating Agreements with CAISO.\n     - CAISO Metered Entities have entered into Meter Service Agreements.\n     - Wholesale Customers are eligible for service.\n     - Each End-Use Customer is eligible for service as a Direct Access End User.\n   - Applicants seeking to serve as Scheduling Coordinators for Convergence Bidding Entities must certify their authorization to represent these entities.\n\nThe document is effective from March 1, 2025, and is version 16.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Scheduling_Coordinator_Certification_&_Termination_and_Convergence_Bidding_Entity_Registration_&_Termination/page_53.jpg",
          "page_num": 53,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Scheduling Coordinator Certification & Termination and Convergence Bidding Entity Registration & Termination",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "053acadc-99ae-4c6b-8432-f1269bbe8988",
        "score": 0.63740385,
        "text": "The document outlines the certification requirements for a Candidate Congestion Revenue Rights (CRR) Holder applicant to participate in the CRR Processes. Key points include:\n\n1. **FERC Order 741 Compliance**: Applicants must meet the minimum participation requirements as per FERC Order 741 and the CAISO Tariff's credit policy. This involves understanding these requirements before applying for Congestion Revenue Rights, with an estimated completion time of about 10 business days.\n\n2. **Financial Criteria**: Entities can satisfy participation requirements by having a net worth of $1 million, total assets of $10 million, or credit support from a guaranty or Letter of Credit from a qualified entity.\n\n3. **Officer Certification and Risk Policies**: An officer from each prospective or existing Market Participant must annually submit a certified statement to CAISO, following a standardized format. The initial certification form is required during the registration process.\n\n4. **Risk Management**: CRR Holders or candidates must provide additional information and attestations regarding their risk management policies, procedures, and controls related to CRR trading activities.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Candidate_CRR_Holder_Registration/page_11.jpg",
          "page_num": 11,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Candidate CRR Holder Registration",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

