  "data": {
    "query": "CAISO regulation service technical requirements performance specifications",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "c94f90dc-e16b-4af4-a290-717fbedae754",
        "score": 0.7042641,
        "text": "The document outlines the certification and testing requirements for Generating Units, System Units, and Load and Proxy Demand Resources (PDRs) under the CAISO Tariff. These entities must comply with CAISO's standards as detailed in the BPM for Compliance Monitoring to submit bids or self-provision Ancillary Services (AS). RDRR and PDR-LSR consumption resources are prohibited from providing AS.\n\nCAISO certifies Multi-Stage Generating Resources for AS at the MSG Configuration level and retains the right to inspect these resources to ensure ongoing compliance with technical requirements. If standards are not met, CAISO may withdraw certification.\n\nThe document specifies that AS certification and capacity are recorded in the Master File after successful testing. Regulation Certification and Testing Requirements are based on CAISO Tariff Section 8.3.4. Units must be certified and tested by CAISO, following specific processes. Units with Automatic Generation Control can be certified for Regulation Up and Down, limited by their 10-minute Ramping capability.\n\nA resource may lose its ability to provide Regulation if its performance falls below a minimum threshold. The ISO provides data to help Scheduling Coordinators monitor performance accuracy, using a weighted average of fifteen-minute intervals.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_211.jpg",
          "page_num": 211,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f04afd46-b9f4-4807-b83e-3eb3b999fe10",
        "score": 0.6676471,
        "text": "The document is part of the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Tariff, specifically Appendix K, which outlines the Ancillary Service Requirements Protocol (ASRP). It focuses on the certification for regulation of Ancillary Service Providers.\n\n### Key Points:\n\n1. **Certification Requirements**:\n   - Ancillary Service Providers must meet specific operating characteristics and technical requirements to provide regulation services, either through a CAISO award or self-provision.\n   - Providers must be certified by CAISO unless temporarily exempted.\n\n2. **Operating Characteristics**:\n   - **Capacity**: The resource must have a rated capacity of at least 500 KW, unless part of an approved aggregation or a storage/Distributed Energy Resource Aggregation of 100 KW or greater.\n   - **Regulation Timing**: Maximum regulation must be reached within 10 minutes.\n   - **Response Capability**: The resource must adjust power levels in response to CAISO's EMS control signals.\n   - **Dispatchability**: Resources must be dispatchable continuously for at least 60 minutes in the Day Ahead Market and 30 minutes in the Real Time Market.\n   - **Accuracy**: The resource's response accuracy to CAISO's EMS signal must exceed 25%.\n\n3. **Technical Requirements**:\n   - **Control**: \n     - A direct, digital control signal from CAISO EMS must meet minimum performance standards.\n     - The resource's response to control signals must also meet these standards, which will be developed and posted by CAISO.\n\nThe document sets forth the criteria and standards necessary for providers to participate in CAISO's regulation services, ensuring reliability and efficiency in energy management.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_1890.jpg",
          "page_num": 1890,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "35dfaa8f-811f-4337-b85f-f0556f8b7562",
        "score": 0.6634152,
        "text": "The document is from California ISO and outlines the audit and testing requirements as per CAISO Tariff Sections 8.9 and 8.10. It is part of the BPM for Compliance Monitoring and includes:\n\n1. **Overview of Auditing and Testing**: \n   - Verification of contracted and self-provided Ancillary Services (AS) and Resource Adequacy Capacity (RUC) by CAISO.\n   - Testing involves Generating Units, Participating Loads, Proxy Demand Resources, and System Resources.\n   - Auditing includes response to CAISO Dispatch Instructions and analysis of telemetry data or interchange schedules.\n   - CAISO can test any Generating Unit, System Unit, System Resource, or related entities.\n   - Operators must notify CAISO if AS or RUC Capacity is unavailable and routinely test their systems to ensure capacity availability.\n   - CAISO may suspend technical eligibility for repeated non-performance.\n\n2. **Performance Audits**:\n   - If a provider fails an audit, CAISO may rescind payments.\n   - Additional actions are required for Resource Adequacy (RA) Resources.\n   - CAISO must develop measures to discourage repeated non-performance by bidders and self-providers.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Compliance_Monitoring/page_9.jpg",
          "page_num": 9,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Compliance Monitoring",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0099cb7c-98c8-469e-89ec-14e44a2984c0",
        "score": 0.6562397,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for evaluating Resource Adequacy (RA) Plans by the California Independent System Operator (CAISO). It specifies that CAISO will assess both annual and monthly RA Plans submitted by Scheduling Coordinators (SC) on behalf of Load Serving Entities (LSE) or Community Choice Aggregators (CPE).\n\n1. **Compliance Evaluation (Tariff Section 40.7.a.i and 40.7.a.ii):**\n   - Each LSE or CPE must meet its allocated megawatt (MW) responsibility for each Transmission Access Charge (TAC) area to serve its load. This involves identifying all resources procured to meet this load annually.\n   - LSEs must also satisfy peak demand and reserve margin requirements by identifying all resources procured to serve the load.\n\n2. **CAISO Review (Tariff Section 40.10.5.3):**\n   - The ISO will conduct three reviews of RA Plans related to Flexible RA Capacity. This includes validating deficiencies if local regulatory authorities haven't set flexible capacity requirements, identifying discrepancies in resources or capacity, and evaluating annual and monthly plans for cumulative deficiency.\n\n3. **Credits and Obligations:**\n   - CAISO accepts credits from Local Regulatory Authorities (LRA) against compliance obligations, provided they net to zero. Credits related to the CPUC\u2019s Cost Allocation Mechanism are accepted as they allocate capacity from known resources without reducing RA capacity.\n   - The CPUC may provide quarterly updates on obligations/credits due to load migration or other factors. CAISO will incorporate these updates into monthly RA requirements but not for existing annual allocations unless the updated allocation is insufficient.\n\n4. **Supply Plan Evaluation (Tariff Section 40.7.b):**\n   - The ISO will evaluate each annual and monthly Supply Plan submitted by an SC on behalf of an RA resource.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of compliance with regulatory requirements and the role of CAISO in ensuring resource adequacy through detailed evaluations and reviews.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Reliability_Requirements/page_25.jpg",
          "page_num": 25,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Reliability Requirements",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ffb85755-9235-4809-98e3-a6c349b9a710",
        "score": 0.6504507,
        "text": "The document outlines the performance evaluation process for resources providing Regulation Up and Regulation Down services. If a resource's performance falls below 25% using Instructed Mileage as the weight, it fails to meet the minimum performance threshold. In such cases, CAISO will not use data from these intervals for calculating Historic Regulation Performance Accuracy.\n\nIf a resource fails to meet the threshold, CAISO issues a warning to the Scheduling Coordinator. The resource's performance is then evaluated over the next two months. If it meets the threshold in at least 15 intervals, the warning is lifted. If not, the resource is decertified. Decertification does not prevent future certification testing.\n\nResources can be recertified if they meet the threshold in subsequent evaluations. Resource-specific System Resources and non-generator resources can also be certified for Regulation Up and Down, with specific requirements for AGC and dynamic interchange capability. Non-generator resources use Regulation Energy Management, with capacity based on four times the maximum Energy.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_212.jpg",
          "page_num": 212,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4fbafabb-fa14-4650-ad45-055ba10d4fad",
        "score": 0.6481131,
        "text": "The document is from the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Reliability Requirements and focuses on \"Information Requirements.\" It outlines:\n\n1. **Content Overview**: \n   - Applicability and process for Load Serving Entity (LSE) election of LSE status.\n   - Programmatic information to be provided by LSEs or CPEs to the ISO.\n   - Requirements for a Resource Adequacy Plan for a Metered Subsystem.\n   - Submittal and validation process at the ISO for Resource Adequacy Plans.\n   - Compliance issues at the ISO with Resource Adequacy Plans.\n\n2. **Applicability and Election Process**:\n   - **Applicability and Scope of Exemptions**: \n     - Based on Section 40 of the ISO Tariff, all LSEs and CPEs must comply unless exempted.\n     - Exemptions apply to LSEs with a metered peak demand of less than 1 MW in the preceding 12 months.\n     - California Public Utilities Code \u00a7 380 provides additional exemptions for certain \"customer generation\" scenarios.\n     - Section 40 applies to LSEs and CPEs not fitting the exemptions.\n     - LSEs with no historic data for metered demand over the specified period cannot claim exemptions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Reliability_Requirements/page_18.jpg",
          "page_num": 18,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Reliability Requirements",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "8afc7bd6-9a9c-461e-b6cf-4d83400ab1cd",
        "score": 0.6457289,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for Local Capacity and Peak Demand validation for Load Serving Entities (LSEs) and Community Choice Aggregators (CPEs) as per the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) guidelines. \n\n1. **Tariff Section 40.7.a.i**: Each LSE or CPE must ensure they have procured sufficient megawatt (MW) capacity for each Transmission Access Charge (TAC) area where they have obligations. This involves meeting MW responsibilities by procuring the necessary capacity in any Local Capacity Area (LCA) within the TAC area.\n\n2. **Tariff Section 40.7.a.ii**: The Scheduling Coordinator (SC) for an LSE must identify all resources used to meet the forecasted peak monthly demand and reserve margin for the relevant reporting period.\n\nThe document is part of the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Reliability Requirements, last revised on March 12, 2025.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Reliability_Requirements/page_40.jpg",
          "page_num": 40,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Reliability Requirements",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6fb8945c-a47c-44e7-a74d-24cc3a2f12e4",
        "score": 0.64504564,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures and requirements related to Load Serving Entities (LSEs) and Central Procurement Entities (CPEs) in the context of resource adequacy for the California Independent System Operator (ISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Compliance Year Definition**: A Compliance Year is defined as the calendar year.\n\n2. **Exemption Requests**: The ISO will respond to exemption requests within five business days. If denied, the response will include data references, and the LSE must comply with ISO Section 40.\n\n3. **Requirements for CPUC LSEs and CPEs**: Scheduling Coordinators must provide necessary information to the ISO as required by the California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC). This includes monthly Resource Adequacy Plans and any additional information specified by the ISO. Submissions must be made at least 45 days before the relevant month.\n\n4. **Resource Adequacy Program**: The ISO Tariff assumes a CPUC capacity-based resource adequacy program. If the CPUC changes its approach, the ISO will adjust its requirements accordingly. Default provisions are in place if the CPUC does not require LSEs or CPEs to provide Reserve Margin information.\n\n5. **Filing Guide**: Additional details and templates are available in the CPUC\u2019s updated Filing Guide online.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of timely and accurate information submission to ensure compliance and resource adequacy.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Reliability_Requirements/page_19.jpg",
          "page_num": 19,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Reliability Requirements",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "fcb0f96b-6984-47dd-9ccb-9cfa59327461",
        "score": 0.6369704,
        "text": "The document outlines standards for metering facilities as part of the CAISO Business Practice Manual. It specifies requirements for both existing and new metering facilities used by CAISO Metered Entities.\n\n### B1: Standards for Existing Metering Facilities\n- **Applicability**: Facilities fully installed by the CAISO Operations Date.\n- **Standards**:\n  - Revenue quality instrument transformers at generator output must have an accuracy of 0.3% or better.\n  - Generator auxiliary load metering must have an overall accuracy of 3% or better.\n  - Revenue quality instrument transformers at transmission metering points must have an accuracy of \u00b10.3% or better.\n- **Modifications**: Any changes to existing facilities must comply with Section B2 standards.\n\n### B2: General Standards for CAISO Meters\n- **Applicability**: New meters installed after the CAISO Operations Date.\n- **Standards**:\n  - Must be revenue quality with a 0.2 Accuracy Class.\n  - Must be remotely accessible, reliable, 60 Hz, three-phase, bi-directional, programmable, and multifunction electronic meters certified for correct operation at service voltage.\n  - Capable of measuring kWh and kVARh, and providing calculated three-phase values for kVAh, kVA.\n  - Must include a demand function with cumulative, rolling, block interval demand calculation, and maximum demand peaks.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Metering/page_81.jpg",
          "page_num": 81,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Metering",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a353a32f-4346-443d-bc1c-b5f0341b6d26",
        "score": 0.63550884,
        "text": "The document outlines the certification requirements for SC (Scheduling Coordinator) Applicants to participate in the CAISO (California Independent System Operator) Markets. Once an application is accepted, a CAISO representative will initiate the certification process. Applicants intending to use a Scheduling Agent must submit a letter of agency with their application.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Financial Security and Participation Requirements**: \n   - Applicants must meet the financial security requirements as per FERC Order 741 and the CAISO Tariff.\n   - Financial security can be established through unsecured credit or approved financial forms.\n   - Information submitted for financial security is confidential.\n\n2. **Minimum Participation Requirements**:\n   - Applicants should understand these requirements before submitting their application.\n   - The process takes about ten business days.\n   - Requirements can be satisfied by having a net worth of $1 million, total assets of $10 million, or credit support from a qualified entity.\n\nAttachment A provides a summary of these certification requirements.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Scheduling_Coordinator_Certification_&_Termination_and_Convergence_Bidding_Entity_Registration_&_Termination/page_21.jpg",
          "page_num": 21,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Scheduling Coordinator Certification & Termination and Convergence Bidding Entity Registration & Termination",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

