        "text": "The document outlines procedures and consequences related to performance audits and compliance testing by the California Independent System Operator (CAISO).\n\n### Consequences of Failure to Pass a Performance Audit (Section 4.2.7)\n- **Notification**: CAISO issues a written notice to the Scheduling Coordinator (SC) for a provider of Ancillary Services (AS) or Resource Adequacy (RA) Capacity if they fail an audit. The notice is also sent to the California Public Utilities Commission (CPUC) or relevant local authority.\n- **Penalties**: Financial penalties are imposed as per the CAISO Tariff, and sanctions may be applied according to the BPM for Rules on Conduct Administration.\n\n### Compliance Testing (Section 4.3)\n- CAISO conducts periodic tests to ensure resources meet performance standards for AS or RUC Capacity. Details are in Operating Procedure 5370.\n- Failure to pass may result in rescission of payments, and disputes can be reviewed by FERC.\n\n### Spinning Reserve Testing (Section 4.3.1)\n- CAISO tests the Spinning Reserve capability of generating units through unannounced dispatch instructions.\n- The response is measured for compliance, and the SC is paid the settlement price for any incremental energy consumed or delivered.\n- The settlement price is the maximum of the resource-specific Settlement Interval Locational Marginal Price (LMP) or the Energy price.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Compliance_Monitoring/page_12.jpg",
          "page_num": 12,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Compliance Monitoring",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ffb85755-9235-4809-98e3-a6c349b9a710",
        "score": 0.64355457,
        "text": "The document outlines the performance evaluation process for resources providing Regulation Up and Regulation Down services. If a resource's performance falls below 25% using Instructed Mileage as the weight, it fails to meet the minimum performance threshold. In such cases, CAISO will not use data from these intervals for calculating Historic Regulation Performance Accuracy.\n\nIf a resource fails to meet the threshold, CAISO issues a warning to the Scheduling Coordinator. The resource's performance is then evaluated over the next two months. If it meets the threshold in at least 15 intervals, the warning is lifted. If not, the resource is decertified. Decertification does not prevent future certification testing.\n\nResources can be recertified if they meet the threshold in subsequent evaluations. Resource-specific System Resources and non-generator resources can also be certified for Regulation Up and Down, with specific requirements for AGC and dynamic interchange capability. Non-generator resources use Regulation Energy Management, with capacity based on four times the maximum Energy.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_212.jpg",
          "page_num": 212,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c9ddec91-d27c-4fdb-aec7-5e04a1840288",
        "score": 0.6395323,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring for California ISO, dated June 2020. It includes a chart (Figure 6.8) showing the frequency of ancillary service scarcities in the 15-minute market for 2018 and 2019, categorized by Regulation Down, Regulation Up, Spin, and Non-Spin services.\n\nSection 6.5 discusses ancillary service compliance testing. It explains that resources undergo performance audits and compliance tests. A performance audit is triggered when a resource fails to meet dispatch during a contingency run, while a compliance test is an unannounced test to check if a resource can produce energy when scheduled. Failing these tests results in a warning, and repeated failures can lead to disqualification from providing the service and rescinding of payments.\n\nIn 2019, 163 performance audits and compliance tests were conducted, with a failure rate of about 20%, similar to 2018. Four failures led to disqualification due to warnings. A new monthly process for performance audits of regulation was introduced in February 2020, requiring resources to pass at least 90% of tests to avoid warnings and potential disqualification.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2019/page_186.jpg",
          "page_num": 186,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": "2019",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e9b18678-d8b2-4bba-9c6f-bb96b1a8e67a",
        "score": 0.6264085,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for calculating a resource's Historic Regulation Performance Accuracy (A4) by the ISO. This is based on a rolling 30-day average of 15-minute accuracy measurements, with separate calculations for Regulation Up and Regulation Down. For newly certified or recertified resources, the initial value is set to the average 30-day Historic Regulation Up Performance Accuracy among all certified resources. If a resource is not scheduled for regulation during the 30 days, the last calculated value is retained.\n\nThe ISO calculates accuracy by summing a resource\u2019s Automatic Generation Control set points for each 4-second interval every 15 minutes and comparing it to the total deviations during that period. Only intervals where the ISO signals a change in direction are counted. For Regulation Up, intervals where the set point is higher than the dispatch point by a certain margin are included. For Regulation Down, intervals where the set point is lower are included. If no mileage occurs in a 15-minute interval, it is excluded from the historical accuracy calculation.\n\nSystem-wide accuracy numbers (A2) for Regulation Up and Down are calculated as a 7-day rolling average of all resources' historical accuracy.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Market_Operations_BPM_Appendices/page_287.jpg",
          "page_num": 287,
          "title": "Market Operations BPM Appendices",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "0d0e754e-1f60-4f72-80a4-82b66b1dc741",
        "score": 0.6262264,
        "text": "The document is a page from the \"Annual Report on Market Issues and Performance\" by the Department of Market Monitoring for California ISO, dated July 2022. It discusses the testing of resources, noting a decrease in the number of tests from 257 in 2020. The failure rate was nearly 30% for unannounced tests and about 8% for performance tests. In 2021, CAISO allowed successful non-spin tests to count as passing for spin tests. For resources like batteries or hybrids, a successful spin test also counts as a passing performance for non-spin tests.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2021/page_191.jpg",
          "page_num": 191,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c2677d54-7817-4899-8d5e-cafddab8c5ea",
        "score": 0.6239848,
        "text": "The document is a section from the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Metering, focusing on ANSI Accuracy Class and Metering Service Verification.\n\n1. **ANSI Accuracy Class**: \n   - Current transformers (CT) must comply with ANSI 0.3 Accuracy Class for specific metering applications.\n   - Correction factor algorithms can be used for accuracy less than \u00b10.3%.\n\n2. **Phase and Polarity Checks (C1.2)**:\n   - Inspectors ensure CT/VT polarity marks follow the same convention.\n   - Phasing must be verified if multiple primary conductors are present.\n\n3. **Ratio Check (C1.3)**:\n   - Inspectors verify the CT/VT ratio matches the manufacturer's nameplate.\n   - A ratio test is required if accuracy cannot be verified within \u00b10.3%.\n\n4. **Burden Check (C1.4)**:\n   - The burden from all equipment in the CT/VT circuit should be less than the designated burden on the nameplate.\n\n5. **Transformer Correction Factor (C1.5)**:\n   - If applied, inspectors review CT/VT data and calculations to ensure compliance with the 0.3 Accuracy Class.\n\n6. **Metering Service Verification (C2)**:\n   - Ensures the metering installation is correctly wired and operational.\n   - Inspectors record service information on the Site Verification Sheet.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Metering/page_134.jpg",
          "page_num": 134,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Metering",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "893e0d16-8015-454c-b95d-a705b5ffa298",
        "score": 0.61447835,
        "text": "The document page is from the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Metering and outlines three tests for meter accuracy and performance:\n\n**B-1: 13.6 Accuracy Test**\n- Confirms meter accuracy under various conditions:\n  - Tested at ambient temperatures of 85\u00b0C and -20\u00b0C.\n  - Tested at power factors of 100%, 50% lag, and 50% lead.\n  - Tested at 0% to 120% of class current.\n- Accuracy curves are provided for all conditions.\n- To pass, the meter must have an accuracy of \u00b1 0.2% at full load with a power factor of 100%, and \u00b1 0.25% at full load with power factors of 50% lag, 50% lead, and at light load with a power factor of 100%.\n\n**B-1: 13.7 Line Voltage Variation Test**\n- Confirms correct operation under varying line voltages (80% to 120% of rated voltage):\n  - Tested at full load and light load with a power factor of 100%.\n- To pass, the meter must:\n  - Operate as specified.\n  - Maintain accuracy as per Section 13.6(c) across the voltage range.\n  - Ensure the power failure backup system does not activate when voltage is between 80% and 120% of rated.\n\n**B-1: 13.8 Momentary Power Loss**\n- Confirms the meter's ability to withstand momentary power outages.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Metering/page_102.jpg",
          "page_num": 102,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Metering",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b217526e-0b70-40ea-af9b-afe4ff06e731",
        "score": 0.60822105,
        "text": "The document page is from the Department of Market Monitoring, California ISO, dated May 2019. It includes a chart (Figure 6.9) showing the frequency of ancillary service scarcities in the 15-minute market for 2017 and 2018. The chart categorizes scarcities into four types: Regulation Down, Regulation Up, Spin, and Non-Spin, with notable increases in Regulation Up during early 2018.\n\nSection 6.5 discusses ancillary service compliance testing. It explains that resources undergo performance audits and compliance tests. A performance audit is triggered when a resource fails to meet dispatch during a contingency run, while a compliance test is unannounced. Failing these tests can lead to warnings, second tests, or disqualification from providing services.\n\nIn 2018, 145 audits and tests were conducted, with a 19% failure rate. Two failures led to disqualification due to existing warnings. A new policy effective January 1, 2019, requires resources below a performance threshold to receive a warning, followed by a performance evaluation within two months. Failure to meet the threshold results in decertification from providing ancillary services.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2018/page_162.jpg",
          "page_num": 162,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2018,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c94f90dc-e16b-4af4-a290-717fbedae754",
        "score": 0.60663986,
        "text": "The document outlines the certification and testing requirements for Generating Units, System Units, and Load and Proxy Demand Resources (PDRs) under the CAISO Tariff. These entities must comply with CAISO's standards as detailed in the BPM for Compliance Monitoring to submit bids or self-provision Ancillary Services (AS). RDRR and PDR-LSR consumption resources are prohibited from providing AS.\n\nCAISO certifies Multi-Stage Generating Resources for AS at the MSG Configuration level and retains the right to inspect these resources to ensure ongoing compliance with technical requirements. If standards are not met, CAISO may withdraw certification.\n\nThe document specifies that AS certification and capacity are recorded in the Master File after successful testing. Regulation Certification and Testing Requirements are based on CAISO Tariff Section 8.3.4. Units must be certified and tested by CAISO, following specific processes. Units with Automatic Generation Control can be certified for Regulation Up and Down, limited by their 10-minute Ramping capability.\n\nA resource may lose its ability to provide Regulation if its performance falls below a minimum threshold. The ISO provides data to help Scheduling Coordinators monitor performance accuracy, using a weighted average of fifteen-minute intervals.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_211.jpg",
          "page_num": 211,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
