{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "regulation up regulation down CAISO technical specifications minimum capacity response time",
    "num_results": 10,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "CAISO",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "73285e11-3f08-4112-9cf3-66d11f7581b8",
        "score": 0.6667094,
        "text": "The document outlines procedures related to Demand Response (DR) options and requirements for the California Independent System Operator (CAISO). Key points include:\n\n- **Bid Dispatchable Options**: Available in 60-minute, 15-minute, and 5-minute intervals.\n- **Master File**: Stores a Demand Response Type attribute, \"DR_TYPE\" as \"RDRR,\" which is view-only and based on valid registration.\n- **Load Curtailment**: For resources selecting the Discrete Real-Time Dispatch Option, the maximum load curtailment is capped at 100 MW. There is no cap for those selecting the Marginal Real-Time Dispatch Option.\n\nExceptions to the 100 MW cap can be requested if valid reasons exist. The Demand Response Provider must submit a request via a CIDI ticket with the subject \"Demand Response Attestation,\" including an attestation as per Appendix H of the Business Process Manual. The attestation must confirm that the resource is at a single site, cannot be split into multiple loads, and cannot operate under the Marginal Real-Time Dispatch Option.\n\nCAISO will review the attestation to ensure no significant reliability issues arise. Approval takes about 10 business days. If a resource approved for over 100 MW increases by 50 MW or more, a new attestation is required.\n\nFor any changes to the resource\u2019s Pmax value, the Scheduling Coordinator must update the Generator Resource Data Template (GRDT).\n\nThe document also mentions requirements for setting up the Masterfile.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Demand_Response/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Demand Response",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "23e8964d-2be0-4e68-8a80-0ef846d3b2db",
        "score": 0.6595732,
        "text": "The document page provides details on two tables related to regulation for resources certified for Regulation Up or Down.\n\n### B.2.8 Regulation Range Curve \u2013 REGULATION tab\n- **Purpose**: Describes the regulation range for a resource.\n- **Columns**:\n  - **Resource ID**: Identifies the resource.\n  - **Segment Type**: REG.\n  - **Segment Number**: Defines up to two regulation ranges (lower and upper).\n    - **Business Rule**: Up to 2 segments allowed.\n  - **Lower MW for Regulation**: Minimum MW output for the current segment.\n    - **Business Rule**: Must be \u2265 MIN_GEN.\n  - **Higher MW for Regulation**: Maximum MW output for the current segment.\n    - **Business Rule**: Must be > Lower MW and \u2264 MAX_GEN.\n\n### B.2.9 Regulation Ramp Rate Curve - REG RAMP tab\n- **Purpose**: Describes the regulation ramp rate for a resource.\n- **Columns**:\n  - **Resource ID**: Identifies the resource.\n  - **Segment Type**: RREG.\n  - **Segment Number**: One ramp rate per resource.\n    - **Business Rule**: 1 segment allowed.\n  - **Worst Regulation Ramp Rate**: Maximum ramp rate under worst conditions (MW/minute).\n    - **Business Rule**: Must be > 0.\n  - **Best Regulation Ramp Rate**: Maximum ramp rate under best conditions (MW/minute).\n    - **Business Rule**: Must be \u2264 Best Operating Ramp Rate and tested Regulation ramp rate.\n  - **Market Regulation Ramp Rate**: Not currently used.\n\nThe document is from Version 90, last revised on December 23, 2024, and is on page 231.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Instruments/page_231.jpg",
          "page_num": 231,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Instruments",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "887dc969-a19f-46d3-9bc0-2c7984d486ae",
        "score": 0.65083206,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements for Regulation Up and Down capacities in the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) market. It specifies that minimum capacities for both Regulation Up and Down must be set for each Ancillary Services (AS) Region and Trading Hour. Additionally, there is a Mileage requirement, which accounts for the expected movement of resources to provide these services. Separate requirements are enforced for the Expanded System Region, and only online Generating Units can fulfill these needs.\n\nCAISO sets its regulation reserve targets based on its forecast and the need to meet WECC and NERC standards. These targets can vary by hour and may change after the Day-Ahead Market runs.\n\nThe Mileage procurement requirement for each hour is determined by the lowest of three values:\n\n1. The product of each service's capacity requirement and a System Mileage Multiplier, which estimates expected generator movement.\n2. The average hourly actual mileage from the previous seven days.\n3. The sum of each resource's specific Mileage multiplier and bid-in regulation capacity, ensuring sufficient Mileage capability to prevent scarcity.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_186.jpg",
          "page_num": 186,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "aa7082d3-e8e5-4b98-9d54-2e61f85fe400",
        "score": 0.64850295,
        "text": "The document is from the California Independent System Operator Corporation and pertains to the Fifth Replacement Electronic Tariff. It outlines the requirements for Regulation capacity during a Settlement Period, specifically for Regulation Up or Down. The requirements are determined by the minimum of three calculations involving the Regulation capacity requirement, System Mileage Multiplier, and average Instructed Mileage.\n\nThe CAISO will publish on OASIS the estimated quantity or percentage of Regulation Reserves needed for each hour of the Day-Ahead Market and each 15-minute period in Real-Time for the Trading Day. It will also publish the average Instructed Mileage from the prior seven days.\n\nSection 8.2.3.1.1 focuses on Regulation Performance, detailing how CAISO measures a resource's response to EMS signals. It involves calculating deviations from Automatic Generation Control set points and using these to determine performance payments. Adjustments are made based on changes in direction signaled by the EMS.\n\nThe CAISO uses a resource's Historic Regulation Performance Accuracy and ramp capability to determine expected Mileage for awarding Regulation Up and Down capacity, calculating a separate Historic Regulation Performance.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_151.jpg",
          "page_num": 151,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ffb85755-9235-4809-98e3-a6c349b9a710",
        "score": 0.644954,
        "text": "The document outlines the performance evaluation process for resources providing Regulation Up and Regulation Down services. If a resource's performance falls below 25% using Instructed Mileage as the weight, it fails to meet the minimum performance threshold. In such cases, CAISO will not use data from these intervals for calculating Historic Regulation Performance Accuracy.\n\nIf a resource fails to meet the threshold, CAISO issues a warning to the Scheduling Coordinator. The resource's performance is then evaluated over the next two months. If it meets the threshold in at least 15 intervals, the warning is lifted. If not, the resource is decertified. Decertification does not prevent future certification testing.\n\nResources can be recertified if they meet the threshold in subsequent evaluations. Resource-specific System Resources and non-generator resources can also be certified for Regulation Up and Down, with specific requirements for AGC and dynamic interchange capability. Non-generator resources use Regulation Energy Management, with capacity based on four times the maximum Energy.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_212.jpg",
          "page_num": 212,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e5cc7ad0-fd2b-41a2-b11f-002c7bc253a9",
        "score": 0.6419084,
        "text": "The document is a section from the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Electronic Tariff. It outlines requirements for resources providing regulation services:\n\n- Resources must achieve specified Ramp Rates (MW/minute) as per their bid.\n- Regulation capacity should not exceed the maximum Ramp Rate times ten minutes.\n- Telemetry to the CAISO Control Center must indicate resource status.\n- Resources must operate fully within the offered Regulation capacity without manual intervention.\n- Ancillary Service Providers must ensure operational CAISO EMS control and SCADA equipment.\n- Regulation capacity must be dispatchable continuously for at least 60 minutes in the Day-Ahead Market and 30 minutes in the Real-Time Market.\n- CAISO will manage energy from resources reaching award capacity and ensure storage resources meet their State of Charge for Ancillary Services.\n- Scheduling Coordinators for Non-Generator Resources may use Regulation Energy Management.\n- CAISO will provide examples in the Business Practice Manual for Day-Ahead and Real-Time Markets.\n\nThe document is dated August 3, 2024, and is from Section 8.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_165.jpg",
          "page_num": 165,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "afd734ad-4086-479a-bb14-4fa23289b4b3",
        "score": 0.6396409,
        "text": "The document discusses the performance of third-party demand response resources in California ISO's resource adequacy supply plans. It highlights two ways to measure aggregated self-reported responses: \n\n1. Capped at the scheduled load reduction for each resource.\n2. Without capping, allowing responses in excess of individual schedules.\n\nThe report notes significant differences between these measures, especially during summer 2024, raising concerns about the performance and measurement of demand response. On average, capped reductions were 54% of scheduled reductions during high load days, while uncapped reductions averaged 113%.\n\nThe graph in Figure 2.12 illustrates these differences, showing that actual performance often exceeds scheduled reductions, indicating potential inaccuracies in available capacity during high demand periods.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2024/page_21.jpg",
          "page_num": 21,
          "title": "Demand response issues and performance 2024",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b125693d-77c0-4837-81ea-0b252c93966f",
        "score": 0.637195,
        "text": "The document page discusses requirements for storage resources in the context of energy regulation. Specifically, it states that if a storage resource receives a 10 MW award for regulation down, it must maintain a state of charge no more than 5 MWh below its maximum capacity. This ensures the resource is adequately prepared to meet regulation demands. The document is version 100 and was last revised on December 23, 2024, appearing on page 136.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_136.jpg",
          "page_num": 136,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b4833b14-66b3-4961-ab57-e7472e09c168",
        "score": 0.63688034,
        "text": "The document page is from the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Market Operations. It includes mathematical formulas and a graph related to capacity allocation for online resources not on load following or regulation. Key formulas define minimum and maximum capacity (MinExCap, MaxExCap), and other capacity-related terms (SRC, NSC, MEC, DAEC, DeRatedCap). Exhibit D-23 visually represents these concepts with a graph showing capacity allocation in terms of MW and $/MWh. The section C.3.2 explains that Regulation Up and Regulation Down are allocated first and pro rata between the most restrictive regulating or operating limits, with no energy bid required for regulation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Market_Operations_BPM_Appendices/page_167.jpg",
          "page_num": 167,
          "title": "Market Operations BPM Appendices",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "71ec0cc7-4c58-4366-b83d-70061258cac3",
        "score": 0.6312514,
        "text": "The document outlines the requirements and examples for energy resources in relation to Regulation Energy Management. It specifies that resources must be able to generate or consume energy for 15 minutes after a Dispatch Instruction. If not, they must meet the same certification requirements as generators.\n\nTwo examples illustrate this:\n\n1. A fully charged resource with 5 MWh can discharge 20 MW for 15 minutes, equating to 20 MW of regulation up capacity.\n2. A completely discharged resource with 2.5 MWh can consume 10 MW for 15 minutes, equating to 10 MW of regulation down capacity.\n\nResources not using Regulation Energy Management are certified like generators.\n\nThe document also provides scenarios for performance evaluation:\n\n- Example A: A resource meets the performance threshold for two consecutive months.\n- Example B: A resource fails to meet the threshold in one of two consecutive months.\n- Examples C & D: A resource meets the threshold in one month, then provides fewer intervals in subsequent months before meeting the threshold again.\n\nA table is included to track the number of intervals provided, performance threshold compliance, and actions taken.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Market_Operations/page_213.jpg",
          "page_num": 213,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

