      {
        "id": "053e0460-60dd-47a9-8bb7-727f912e63be",
        "score": 0.6420932,
        "text": "The document page discusses the resource adequacy program managed by the California ISO, which ensures that load serving entities (LSEs) have sufficient capacity to meet electricity demand. It outlines three types of capacity requirements: system resource capacity for peak demand, local resource capacity for specific areas, and flexible resource capacity for ramping periods. LSEs must demonstrate their capacity procurement to the California ISO through filings.\n\nThe section on system resource adequacy focuses on the availability and performance of these resources, especially during tight system hours when alerts or emergencies are issued. Regulatory requirements are set by the California ISO in collaboration with the CEC, CPUC, and other authorities. LSEs must meet these requirements by filing annual and monthly supply plans, showing they have procured 90% of their system resource adequacy obligations for the five summer months in the compliance year.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/report/2021/page_256.jpg",
          "page_num": 256,
          "title": "Annual Report on Market Issues & Performance",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2c4c6bda-4bad-4fc1-a765-acde15a21c44",
        "score": 0.6353785,
        "text": "The document is a section from the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Electronic Tariff, specifically Section 40, dated February 5, 2025. It discusses the criteria for Resource Adequacy Compliance and Qualifying Capacity.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Resource Adequacy Compliance**: Load Serving Entities (LSE) or CPEs (Central Procurement Entities) must use committed Resource Adequacy Capacity to meet requirements set by the CPUC (California Public Utilities Commission), local regulatory authorities, or federal agencies. They are not subject to penalties if they meet these obligations.\n\n2. **CAISO Default Qualifying Capacity Criteria (Section 40.8)**:\n   - **Applicability**: Criteria apply when the CPUC or local authorities haven't set criteria for resource types eligible for Qualifying Capacity. CAISO uses these criteria until notified otherwise by the CPUC.\n   - **Nuclear and Thermal**: These generating units, excluding certain qualifying facilities, must be participating generators or part of a system unit. Their capacity is based on net dependable capacity as defined by NERC data.\n   - **Hydro**: Mentioned as a category but details are not provided in the visible text.\n\nThe document outlines the regulatory framework and criteria for determining and utilizing qualifying capacity for resource adequacy.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Fifth_Replacement_FERC_Electric_Tariff/page_1093.jpg",
          "page_num": 1093,
          "title": "Fifth Replacement FERC Electric Tariff",
