        "text": "The document is a section from the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Tariff, specifically Appendix K, dated August 3, 2024. It outlines regulations for certification and operation of resources providing Regulation and Spinning Reserve services.\n\n### Regulation Service (A 12 - A 14)\n- **A 12**: Scheduling Coordinators can submit bids for Regulation services from certified resources starting with the Day-Ahead Market.\n- **A 13**: Certification remains in force unless withdrawn by the Scheduling Coordinator or revoked by CAISO for non-compliance with communication and control technology requirements.\n- **A 13.1**: If certification was based on prior technology, CAISO requires installation of a standard communication system. Failure to comply can lead to revocation.\n- **A 14**: Certification revocation is governed by CAISO Tariff provisions.\n\n### Spinning Reserve Service (Part B)\n- **B 1**: Ancillary Service Providers must meet specific requirements to offer Spinning Reserve services.\n- **B 1.1**: Resources must have a rated capacity of at least 500 KW, or 100 KW if part of an approved aggregation.\n- **B 1.2**: Resources with governors must respond to frequency deviations with specified performance standards:\n  - 5% droop (4% for combustion turbines)\n  - +/- 0.036 Hz deadband\n  - Power output changes within one second for deviations outside the deadband\n  - Generators must not inhibit real power response unless necessary for operational constraints.\n\nThe document emphasizes compliance with CAISO standards and the importance of maintaining communication and control systems for certification.",
