        "text": "The document is part of the California Independent System Operator Corporation's Fifth Replacement Electronic Tariff, specifically Appendix S, dated August 3, 2024. It outlines procedures related to reductions in generating facility capacity and the fast track process for interconnection.\n\n### 1.4 Reductions in Generating Facility Capacity\n\n- **De Minimis Capacity Reductions (1.4.1):** \n  - If an Interconnection Customer's facility reduces its capacity by no more than the greater of 5% of its capacity or 10 MW, and not exceeding 25% of its capacity, it is not considered a breach of obligations under the CAISO Tariff or Generator Interconnection Agreement.\n  - The capacity value is based on the current Generator Interconnection Agreement.\n  - No capacity reductions should affect the customer's responsibilities under the agreements.\n\n### Section 2: Fast Track Process\n\n#### 2.1 Applicability\n- The Fast Track Process is for interconnecting a Small Generating Facility with the CAISO Controlled Grid if it is larger than 2 MW.\n- The facility must meet specific codes, standards, and certification requirements, and be deemed safe by the Participating Transmission Owner (TO).\n\n#### 2.2 Initial Review\n- Within 15 business days of receiving a complete Interconnection Request, the Participating TO must perform an initial review.\n- The review includes:\n  - **Screens (2.2.1):**\n    - **2.2.1.1:** The interconnection point must be on the Participating TO's Distribution System under the CAISO Tariff.\n    - **2.2.1.2:** For radial distribution circuits, the aggregated generation should not exceed 15% of the line section's peak load.\n    - **2.2.1.3:** For network protectors, the facility must be on the load side.\n\nThe document provides guidelines to ensure compliance and safety in the interconnection process.",
